  const nmcMentalHealth = [
    { scenario: "A patient presents with suicidal ideation on an NHS ward", management: "conduct a thorough risk assessment using a validated tool, ask directly about suicidal thoughts/plans/means (asking does NOT increase risk), ensure the patient is in a safe environment, implement continuous observation (1:1 nursing if high risk), remove potential ligature points and harmful items, refer to the mental health liaison team, and document the assessment comprehensively", topic: "Suicide Risk Assessment", difficulty: 3 },
    { scenario: "A patient is detained under Section 2 of the Mental Health Act 1983", management: "Section 2 allows detention for up to 28 days for assessment. It requires two medical recommendations (one Section 12 approved) and an application from an AMHP. The patient has the right to appeal to a Mental Health Tribunal within 14 days. Explain the patient's rights, provide information leaflet, ensure access to an Independent Mental Health Advocate (IMHA)", topic: "MHA Section 2", difficulty: 3 },
    { scenario: "A patient on an NHS ward is acutely agitated and threatening violence towards staff", management: "ensure personal safety and the safety of other patients, use de-escalation techniques first (calm voice, non-threatening body language, offer choices, listen to grievances), clear the area of other patients, call for help if escalation continues, use restrictive interventions only as a last resort and for the minimum time necessary, and complete a Datix incident report", topic: "De-escalation and Aggression", difficulty: 3 },
    { scenario: "A patient with schizophrenia is experiencing command auditory hallucinations telling them to harm themselves", management: "take the hallucinations seriously, assess the content and the patient's intention to act on commands, increase observation level, ensure the environment is safe, administer PRN antipsychotic medication if prescribed, contact the psychiatric team urgently, and do not dismiss or agree with the hallucinations — acknowledge the patient's experience", topic: "Command Hallucinations", difficulty: 4 },
    { scenario: "A patient on lithium therapy presents with tremor, nausea, blurred vision, and drowsiness", management: "suspect lithium toxicity — check urgent serum lithium level (therapeutic range 0.4-1.0 mmol/L, toxic >1.5 mmol/L), withhold lithium, check U&Es (renal function), ensure adequate hydration, monitor ECG (lithium can cause arrhythmias), and escalate urgently. Common precipitants: dehydration, NSAIDs, ACE inhibitors, diuretics", topic: "Lithium Toxicity", difficulty: 4 },
    { scenario: "A nurse is supporting a patient with anorexia nervosa who is admitted for medical stabilisation with a BMI of 13", management: "this is high-risk refeeding — implement a structured refeeding protocol, start at low calorie intake (5-10 kcal/kg/day) and increase gradually, monitor for refeeding syndrome (hypophosphataemia, hypokalaemia, hypomagnesaemia), check electrolytes daily, continuous cardiac monitoring, and provide therapeutic support with the eating disorders team", topic: "Refeeding Syndrome Risk", difficulty: 4 },
    { scenario: "A patient with depression has been started on an SSRI (sertraline) 1 week ago and presents with increased anxiety and restlessness", management: "this is a recognised early side effect of SSRIs (initial activation/anxiety typically resolves within 2-4 weeks), reassure the patient, assess for suicidal ideation (increased risk in first 2-4 weeks, especially in young adults), arrange close follow-up, consider short-term anxiolytic if severe, and do NOT stop the antidepressant abruptly", topic: "SSRI Initiation Side Effects", difficulty: 3 },
    { scenario: "A patient is brought to A&E by police under Section 136 of the Mental Health Act", management: "Section 136 allows police to remove a person from a public place to a 'place of safety' (usually a Section 136 suite or A&E) for up to 24 hours (extendable by 12 hours) for mental health assessment. The patient must be assessed by a doctor and AMHP. Ensure the patient's rights are explained, and provide a safe, therapeutic environment during the assessment", topic: "MHA Section 136", difficulty: 3 },
    { scenario: "A nurse is caring for a patient with borderline personality disorder (BPD/EUPD) who has self-harmed by cutting", management: "treat wounds with compassion and without judgement, conduct a thorough risk assessment (self-harm is NOT always a suicide attempt but must be assessed), use a trauma-informed approach, validate the patient's distress without reinforcing self-harm, develop a collaborative safety plan, and refer to psychological therapy (DBT is evidence-based for BPD)", topic: "Self-Harm Management", difficulty: 3 },
    { scenario: "A patient on clozapine therapy requires routine blood monitoring", management: "clozapine requires mandatory blood monitoring for neutrophil counts due to risk of agranulocytosis (potentially fatal): weekly for first 18 weeks, fortnightly for weeks 18-52, then monthly after 1 year. The medication cannot be dispensed without a satisfactory blood result registered on the monitoring service. Also monitor for metabolic syndrome, sedation, constipation, and myocarditis", topic: "Clozapine Monitoring", difficulty: 4 },
  ];
